TI  - The structural characteristics, physicochemical properties, rheological behavior and anti-obesity effects of polysaccharides from Pueraria lobata: In-depth study focusing on the gut microbiota-hepatic FGF21 signaling
PY  - 2026
T2  - Food Research International
VL  - 231
C7  - 118717
DO  - 10.1016/j.foodres.2026.118717
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105030871537&doi=10.1016%2Fj.foodres.2026.118717&partnerID=40&md5=0743d22cfaca28e9b6ce915bf5c7974a
AB  - Obesity and related metabolic disorders pose a global health challenge. Bioactive polysaccharides have emerged as potential modulators of obesity through gut microbiota regulation. In this study, Pueraria lobata polysaccharide (UPLP) was prepared via ultrasonic-assisted extraction method. Chemically analysis identified that UPLP as a glucose-rich polysaccharide fraction containing 96.33% glucose with trace amounts of xylose (1.02%), galactose (0.15%), and galacturonic acid (1.12%). The molecular weight distribution shows that the main component of UPLP has a molecular weight of 152.63 kDa, presenting a smooth and dense sheet-like structure and possessing excellent thermodynamic and rheological properties. In vivo, daily UPLP administration markedly attenuated HFD-induced obesity, improved glucose tolerance and insulin sensitivity, and normalized serum lipid profiles. Hepatic analyses revealed reduced steatosis, transaminase activity, and pro-inflammatory cytokines, alongside enhanced antioxidant capacity. UPLP strengthened intestinal barrier integrity by upregulating ZO-1 and Occludin, increasing goblet cells, and reducing serum D-lactate. 16S rRNA sequencing showed that UPLP restored microbial α-diversity, enriched beneficial taxa (Lactobacillus, Dubosiella, Mailhella), and elevated colonic butyrate level. Metabolomics and multi-omics analyses indicated UPLP modulated amino acid, linoleic acid, and tryptophan metabolism, and activated hepatic FGF21 signaling (AKT, ERK, STAT3), promoting fatty acid β-oxidation and suppressing inflammation. Collectively, UPLP mitigates obesity via gut microbiota remodeling, SCFA-mediated intestinal repair, and hepatic FGF21 pathway activation, underscoring its potential as a functional food for metabolic disorder prevention. © 2024
