TI  - Gut-health pharmacology
PY  - 2024
T2  - Biochemical and Molecular Pharmacology in Drug Discovery
SP  - 377
EP  - 399
DO  - 10.1016/B978-0-443-16013-4.00018-X
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85202907339&doi=10.1016%2FB978-0-443-16013-4.00018-X&partnerID=40&md5=b3e307c43a2b7421fbafb9f07f290e75
AB  - Plant-based therapies, renowned for their historical use in disease prevention, have now garnered increased attention due to their potential in alleviating the gut microbiome. Recent revelations concerning the pivotal role of the gut microbiome in human health have illuminated a novel dimension to the efficacy of plant metabolites. Dysbiosis, the disruption of the gut microbiome, has been implicated in a spectrum of health issues, encompassing gastrointestinal conditions and systemic diseases. The intricate gut-brain communication network and the microbiota-dependent pathways underscore the far-reaching implications of plant-based interventions in diseases like cardiovascular conditions and certain cancers. Notably, polyphenols and carbohydrates have demonstrated prebiotic attributes, bolstering beneficial gut bacteria. Short-chain fatty acids, produced through carbohydrate fermentation, act as critical signaling molecules impacting gut function. Berberine, d-limonene, has emerged as a potent regulator of gut microbiota, impacting the Microbiota-Gut-Brain axis and promoting the growth of beneficial bacteria. While natural products exhibit immense therapeutic potential, practical limitations often impede their use. The advent of nanoformulation techniques, addressing issues of solubility, specificity, and bioavailability, presents a promising solution to harness the full potential of plant-based therapies in the context of the gut microbiome. Therefore, the present article tries to encompass the role of plant secondary metabolites in improvement of gut microbiome as well as ways to eliminate the issues of drug delivery for effective therapy in gut dysbiosis. © 2024 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
